  "prompt": "What is the mitochondria? What function does it have?",
  "response": "The mitochondria is an organelle found in most eukaryotic cells, often referred to as the \"powerhouse of the cell\" due to its crucial role in energy production. Here are its key functions:\n\n1. Energy Production\n- Generates ATP (adenosine triphosphate) through cellular respiration\n- Converts nutrients into energy through the electron transport chain\n- Produces about 90% of a cell's chemical energy\n\n2. Cellular Metabolism\n- Plays a key role in metabolic processes\n- Helps regulate cellular metabolism\n- Involved in breaking down and converting nutrients\n\n3. Cell Signaling\n- Participates in cell communication\n- Helps regulate cell growth and cell death\n- Involved in cellular stress responses\n\n4. Calcium Storage and Regulation\n- Stores and releases calcium ions\n- Important for cell signaling and muscle contraction\n\n5. Heat Generation\n- Helps generate body heat through metabolic processes\n\n6. Programmed Cell Death\n- Plays a role in apoptosis (programmed cell death)\n- Can trigger cell death signals\n\n7. Unique Characteristics\n- Contains its own DNA (mitochondrial DNA)\n- Can reproduce independently within the cell\n- Inherited primarily from the mother\n\nThe mitochondria is essential for cell survival and proper functioning across most living organisms.",
